Provided the elections take place as scheduled on 07 December 2020, there are two major factors to consider: In the presidential elections, the NPP candidate Nana Akufo-Addo is the incumbent and has previously served as minister of foreign affairs before his first term. As the incumbent, he is likely to get re-elected, however, the contest in the 2016 election was so close (53.72% vs. 44.53%) that, according to an anecdote, "[t]he election results were announced on 9 December 2016 due to a delay of voting in two areas. At 19:51 local time, Mahama called Akufo-Addo to concede defeat. At 20:45, the Electoral Commission declared that Akufo-Addo had defeated Mahama in a single round." https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Ghanaian_general_election

Ghana appears to have handled the covid-19 pandemic well with limited deaths and the majority of infections having recovered. The latest election polls show Mahama (NDC) to have 48% and the incumbent Akufo-Addo (NPP) to have 35% and 17% for neither if the election had been carried out in June. Ghana elections are traditionally close. Probability of a majority of seats for the NPP is marginal at the moment.

For the NPP to lose it's majority it has to lose a net 32 seats. Ghana has had relatively stable elections for nearly 30 years. Since there were only two winners last time, I'm discounting the plurality option. Elections could be counted on, if not for COVID-19. Ghana uses "First Pass The Post" system for parliamentary elections, in which according to Wikipedia: It is more likely that a single party will hold a majority of legislative seats. Much more research is needed.
